body:
Consider this, which sometimes catches out Verilog newcomers:

```systemverilog
module t;
  int a = 42;
  always @* a = 100;
  initial #10 $display("a should be 42, but is: %0d", a);
endmodule
```

On event based simulators, the always block is never run, because it has no sensitivities (no variables read inside), so `a` will be observed as `42` in the `$display`. Verilator executes it at time zero (as if it was an `always_comb`), so `a` is printed as 100.

There should be a warning that this (`always @*` with nothing read inside) will not match event based simulators, and that you probably meant `always_comb`.

Note with -Wall there is PROCASSINIT, but if you omit the static initializer (which I only added for emphasis), you get nothing (and on event based 4 state simulators `a` would remain an x value).

